The 462nd ''Volksgrenadier'' Division was originally formed in October 1942 as a replacement division in the French town of [[Nancy, France|Nancy]], in the Lorraine Province, under the command of ''Generalmajor'' (major general) Otto Schilling. It took responsibility for many of the units of the former 182nd Reserve Division and was expanded with various fortress and training troops stationed at [[Luxembourg]], [[Saarburg]] and [[Metz]]. After [[D-Day]] it was designated as a ''[[Volksgrenadier]]'' division and reorganised for combat and was dispatched to the frontlines in August 1944.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007|pp=128–129}}

At the start of November 1944, the division, less the 1216th Grenadier Regiment which had been transferred to the [[19th Volksgrenadier Division (Wehrmacht)|19th ''Volksgrenadier'' Division]], was defending the town of Metz from the United States [[Third Army (United States)|Third Army]]. At this stage of the war, the division numbered 7,000 personnel. It surrendered the town on 28 November, having lost two commanders during the [[Battle of Metz|siege]]; Lübbe had suffered a stroke and his replacement, Kittel, was wounded in action on 22 November. Over 1,000 men evaded capture by virtue of being evacuated as wounded prior to the fall of Metz. The division was disbanded shortly afterwards.{{sfn|Mitcham|2007|pp=128–129}}

==Commanders==
*''Generalmajor'' Otto Schilling (5 October – 4 December 1942);
*''Generalleutnant'' Ernest Guntzel (5–17 December 1942);
*''Generalleutnant'' Hans von Sommerfeld (17 December 1942 – 14 July 1944);
*''Generalleutnant'' Walter Krause (15 July – 14 October 1944);
*''Generalleutnant'' [[Vollrath Lübbe]] (15 October – 8 November 1944);
*''Generalmajor'' [[Heinrich Kittel]] (8 November – 22 November 1944);
*''Oberst'' Joachim Wagner (22–28 November 1944).{{sfn|Mitcham|2007|pp=128–129}}

